So far, I have found the expression
 S_(3n) = 3n/2 (6 + 6n * 3 - 3).  Because we are told that
\begin{align*}
S_{3n} = CS_{n}
\end{align*}
for some constant $C,$ then
\begin{align*}
S_{3n} = C * 1/2 (√3 * 3 + 3).
\end{align*}
Expanding these two equations leads to the 2 equations
\begin{align*}
S_{3n} = 3n/2 (6n + 9) = 3n/2(6 + 6n * 3 - 3).
\end{align*}
Therefore in order for the first equation to equal the second equation, we must have the constants
\begin{align*}
C = 3.
\end{align*}
However, consider the ratio of $S_{3n} / S_{n}$
\begin{align*}
\frac{3n/(6n + 9)}{n^2/(6 + 6n * 3 - 3)} = C.
\end{align*}
Trying to solve as a quadratic we get  three solutions, which are $\boxed{4}$, $\boxed{-1}$ and $\boxed{0}$</think>
