There exists an arithmetic sequence whose sum of the first $n$ terms, $S_n$, can be written as a function of the first term, $a$, as $S_n = a * n + 3 *n * (n - 1) / 2$, and whose sum of the first $3n$ terms, $S_{3n}$, can be written as a function of the first term, $a$, as $S_{3n} = a * 3n + 9 *n * (3n - 1) / 2$.
By hypothesis,
\begin{align*}
S_{3n} = C * S_n <\Rightarrow> C = \frac{S_{3n}}{S_n} = \frac{a(3n) + \frac{9n(3n - 1)}{2}}{a*n + \frac{3n(n - 1)}{2}} = \frac{2a(3n) + 9n(3n - 1)}{a(2n) + 3n(n - 1)}=\frac{a(6n) + 9n(3n - 1)}{a(2n) + 3n(n - 1)}.
\end{align*}
gcd is $3n$, so (divide both numerator and denominator by $3n$)
\begin{align*}
C = \frac{2a + 9(n - 1)}{2a + 3(n - 1)} = 3.
\end{align*}
To recapitulate, this happens when $a*3 = 4$. Thus, the first term is: $\boxed{4}$.
</answer>

